import osmnx as ox
import networkx as nx

# Obtain the graph
G = ox.graph_from_place('Amsterdam', network_type='bike')

# Define the latitude and longitude of the origin and destination points
origin_point = (52.362935, 4.884141)  # Example origin point
destination_point = (52.373278, 4.900836)  # Example destination point

# Find the nearest nodes for the origin and destination points
orig = ox.distance.nearest_nodes(G, origin_point[1], origin_point[0])
dest = ox.distance.nearest_nodes(G, destination_point[1], destination_point[0])

# Define the intermediate points
stops = [(52.360145, 4.890038), (52.376920, 4.902979), (52.361589, 4.896130), (52.366064, 4.902616)]

# Find the nearest nodes for the specified intermediate points
nodes = [ox.distance.nearest_nodes(G, stop[1], stop[0]) for stop in stops]

# Initialize the path with the origin
path = [orig]

# Find the shortest paths between consecutive pairs of nodes and extend the path
for i in range(len(nodes) - 1):
    path += nx.shortest_path(G, nodes[i], nodes[i + 1], weight='length')[1:]

# Add the destination to the path
path += [dest]

# Print the complete path
print(path)

# Plot the graph with the shortest path
fig, ax = ox.plot_graph_route(G, path, route_linewidth=6, node_size=10, bgcolor='k')

import osmnx as ox
import networkx as nx

# Obtain the graph
G = ox.graph_from_place('Amsterdam', retain_all=False, truncate_by_edge=False, simplify=True, custom_filter='["waterway"~"canal"]')

# Define the latitude and longitude of the origin and destination points
origin_point = (52.362935, 4.884141)  # Example origin point
destination_point = (52.373278, 4.900836)  # Example destination point

# Find the nearest nodes for the origin and destination points
orig = ox.distance.nearest_nodes(G, origin_point[1], origin_point[0])
dest = ox.distance.nearest_nodes(G, destination_point[1], destination_point[0])

# Find the shortest path between the origin and destination nodes
route = nx.shortest_path(G, orig, dest)

# Find the nodes' coordinates along the route
nodes_coordinates = [G.nodes[node] for node in route]

# Calculate the center of the nodes' coordinates
avg_latitude = sum(node['y'] for node in nodes_coordinates) / len(nodes_coordinates)
avg_longitude = sum(node['x'] for node in nodes_coordinates) / len(nodes_coordinates)

# Print the center coordinates
print(f"Center latitude: {avg_latitude}, Center longitude: {avg_longitude}")

# Plot the graph with the shortest path
fig, ax = ox.plot_graph_route(G, route, route_linewidth=6, node_size=3, bgcolor='k')

import osmnx as ox

# Define the latitude and longitude of the center point
latitude = 52.373278
longitude = 4.900836


# Fetch the walkable network data
G = ox.graph_from_point((latitude, longitude), dist=2000, network_type='walk')

# Define the speed of walking (meters per second)
walk_speed = 1.4

# Calculate the time in seconds that corresponds to 10 minutes
target_time_minutes = 10
target_time_seconds = target_time_minutes * 60

# Filter reachable nodes based on the walking time
reachable_nodes = []
for node in G.nodes:
    if 'x' in G.nodes[node] and 'y' in G.nodes[node]:
        dist = ox.distance.great_circle_vec(latitude, longitude, G.nodes[node]['y'], G.nodes[node]['x'])
        time_to_node = dist / walk_speed
        if time_to_node <= target_time_seconds:
            reachable_nodes.append(node)

# Create a subgraph of reachable nodes
reachable_graph = G.subgraph(reachable_nodes)

# Plot the walkable network within 10 minutes
ox.plot_graph(reachable_graph)
